What is an Object?

An object stores data as key-value pairs.

Example:

let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27,
    city: "Coimbatore"
};

Here:

name, age, city → Keys (Properties)
"Priya", 27, "Coimbatore" → Values
Creating Objects
Method 1 (Recommended)
let employee = {
    id: 101,
    name: "Lokesh",
    salary: 50000
};

console.log(employee);

Output

{
  id: 101,
  name: "Lokesh",
  salary: 50000
}
Empty Object
let person = {};

person.name = "Priya";
person.age = 27;

console.log(person);

Output

{
  name: "Priya",
  age: 27
}
Accessing Object Properties ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

There are two ways.

1. Dot Notation (Most Common)
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

console.log(student.name);
console.log(student.age);

Output

Priya
27
2. Bracket Notation
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

console.log(student["name"]);
console.log(student["age"]);

Output

Priya
27
When to Use Bracket Notation

Useful when the property name is stored in a variable.

let key = "name";

let student = {
    name: "Priya"
};

console.log(student[key]);

Output

Priya
Modify Properties
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

student.age = 28;

console.log(student);

Output

{
  name: "Priya",
  age: 28
}
Add New Property
let student = {
    name: "Priya"
};

student.city = "Coimbatore";

console.log(student);

Output

{
  name: "Priya",
  city: "Coimbatore"
}
Delete Property
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

delete student.age;

console.log(student);

Output

{
  name: "Priya"
}
Nested Objects ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Objects can contain other objects.

let employee = {
    id: 101,
    name: "Lokesh",

    address: {
        city: "Coimbatore",
        state: "Tamil Nadu",
        pincode: 641005
    }
};

console.log(employee.address.city);

Output

Coimbatore
Another Example
let user = {
    name: "Priya",

    contact: {
        email: "priya@gmail.com",
        mobile: "9876543210"
    }
};

console.log(user.contact.email);

Output

priya@gmail.com
Object Methods ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Objects can contain functions.

let student = {

    name: "Priya",

    greet: function () {
        console.log("Welcome!");
    }

};

student.greet();

Output

Welcome!
Using this
let employee = {

    name: "Lokesh",

    greet() {
        console.log("Hello " + this.name);
    }

};

employee.greet();

Output

Hello Lokesh

this refers to the current object.

Object Destructuring ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Extract values from an object into variables.

Without destructuring:

let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

let name = student.name;
let age = student.age;

With destructuring:

let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

let { name, age } = student;

console.log(name);
console.log(age);

Output

Priya
27
Rename Variables
let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

let { name: studentName, age: studentAge } = student;

console.log(studentName);
console.log(studentAge);

Output

Priya
27
Loop Through an Object

Use for...in.

let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27,
    city: "Coimbatore"
};

for (let key in student) {
    console.log(key, student[key]);
}

Output

name Priya
age 27
city Coimbatore
Built-in Object Methods
Object.keys()

Returns all keys.

let student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

console.log(Object.keys(student));

Output

["name", "age"]
Object.values()

Returns all values.

console.log(Object.values(student));

Output

["Priya", 27]
Object.entries()

Returns key-value pairs.

console.log(Object.entries(student));

Output

[
  ["name", "Priya"],
  ["age", 27]
]


Interview Questions ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
1. What is an object?

An object is a collection of key-value pairs used to store related data and behavior.

2. Difference between Dot Notation and Bracket Notation?
Dot notation: student.name
Bracket notation: student["name"]
Use bracket notation when the property name is stored in a variable.
3. What is Object Destructuring?

Object destructuring lets you extract properties into variables.

Example:

let { name, age } = student;
4. What does this refer to in an object?

this refers to the current object that is calling the method.
